The issue you're experiencing arises from how you're passing props to your `ControlPanel` component. In React, props are passed to a component within a single `props` object. When you define your `ControlPanel` component as `ControlPanel(images, selectedImageIds)`, you are actually attempting to destructure `props`, but the syntax is incorrect.

Instead, props should be received as a single object and destructured within the component's function body, as in `ControlPanel(props)`, and then you use object destructuring to extract `images` and `selectedImageIds` from `props`.

Here's how to correctly define and utilize props within your `ControlPanel`:

```jsx
// ControlPanel/index.jsx
import React, { useContext } from "react";
import { Tabs } from "antd";
import { SourceContext } from "../../contexts/SourceContext";

const { TabPane } = Tabs;

// Destructure props correctly here
const ControlPanel = ({ images, selectedImageIds }) => {
  // ...rest of your code as before

  // Now this line should function correctly if images is an array
  const selectedImages = images.filter((image) =>
    selectedImageIds.has(image.id)
  );

  return (
    // Rest of your component
  );
};

export default ControlPanel;
```

And here's how you should pass `images` and `selectedImageIds` as props to `ControlPanel`:

```jsx
// ImagesPage/index.jsx
// ... other imports ...

const ImagesPage = () => {
  // ...state definitions...

  return (
    <>
      <ImageActionBar />
      <SourceControl /*...props...*/ />
      <Content style={{ margin: "24px 16px 0", overflow: "initial" }}>
        <ImageGrid /*...props...*/ />
        {/* Pass images and selectedImageIds to the ControlPanel */}
        <ControlPanel images={images} selectedImageIds={selectedImageIds} />
      </Content>
    </>
  );
};

export default ImagesPage;
```

Make sure when you use `ControlPanel` in `ImagesPage` (or wherever it's used in the component tree), you are passing `images` and `selectedImageIds` as props to `ControlPanel`. If these props are not passed correctly, the `images` variable inside `ControlPanel` will be `undefined`, resulting in an error when you try to call `.filter` on it.

Any props you pass to a component must also be received correctly inside that component to avoid `undefined` issues. Always check your props usage and confirm they are being passed and received as expected.
